

Southwest China's Yunnan Province, praised as a flora paradise, sold abroad 9.16 million U.S. dollars worth of fresh cut flowers in the first 10 months of this year, a year-on-year increment of 2.66 million U.S. dollars, or 88.1 percent.

According to local customs sources, the exports quantity went up 8.7 percent to 3,858 tons, with average price per kilogram up 73 percent to reach 2.37 U.S. dollars.

Most of the exports were carnations, roses and lilies, the sources said.

Between January and October, Hong Kong surpassed Japan to become the top target market of Yunnan flowers with an import volume of 2.51 million U.S. dollars, up 400 percent. Japan ranked second with the import value at 2.5 million U.S. dollars, up 23.8 percent.

The two were followed by Singapore, Thailand, Australia, Malaysia and the Republic of Korea, the local customs sources said.

Over the 10 months, foreign-funded businesses accounted for 54.6 percent of Yunnan's total fresh cut flower exports, up from 26.1 percent a year earlier. They exported five million U.S. dollars worth of fresh cut flowers, up 290 percent, the sources added.

